<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-more-convergence-tests-for-series"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>More Convergence Tests for Series</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      The tests in <xref ref="sec-convergence-tests-for-series"/> are enough
      for many examples, but two further tools are often useful. The first
      concerns products of convergent series, and the second sharpens the
      ratio test in the borderline case when the quotient of consecutive terms
      tends to <m>1</m>.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-series-cauchy-products">
    <title>Cauchy Products</title>

    <p>
      Given two series
      <me>
        \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n
        \qquad \text{and} \qquad
        \sum_{n=0}^\infty b_n,
      </me>
      their <term>Cauchy product</term><idx>Cauchy product</idx> is the series
      <me>
        \sum_{n=0}^\infty c_n,
        \qquad
        c_n:=\sum_{k=0}^n a_kb_{n-k}.
      </me>
      The coefficient <m>c_n</m> is the sum of all products whose indices add
      to <m>n</m>.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-mertens-series">
      <title>Mertens' Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose
          <me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n = A
            \qquad \text{and} \qquad
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty b_n = B
          </me>
          both converge, and suppose that at least one of these series
          converges absolutely. Then the Cauchy product
          <me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty c_n
          </me>
          converges, and
          <me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty c_n = AB.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          We omit the proof. See <xref ref="biblio-rudin-pma"/>, Chapter 3,
          or <xref ref="biblio-bartle-sherbert"/>, Chapter 9.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="eg-cauchy-product-geometric-square">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>|x|&lt;1</m>. The Cauchy product of
          <me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty x^n
            \qquad \text{with itself}
          </me>
          has coefficients
          <me>
            c_n=\sum_{k=0}^n x^k x^{n-k}=(n+1)x^n.
          </me>
          Since the geometric series converges absolutely for <m>|x|&lt;1</m>
          by <xref ref="prop-geometric-series"/>, Mertens' theorem gives
          <me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty (n+1)x^n
            =
            \left(\sum_{n=0}^\infty x^n\right)^2
            =
            \frac{1}{(1-x)^2}.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-cauchy-product-conditional-divergence">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The Cauchy product of two conditionally convergent series may
          diverge. Consider
          <me>
            a_n=b_n=\frac{(-1)^{n+1}}{\sqrt{n}}
            \qquad (n \ge 1).
          </me>
          By the alternating series test
          (<xref ref="prop-alternating-series-test"/>), the series
          <m>\sum_{n=1}^\infty a_n</m> converges. It is not absolutely
          convergent, because <m>\sum 1/\sqrt{n}</m> diverges by the
          <m>p</m>-series test (<xref ref="prop-p-series-test"/>).
        </p>

        <p>
          If <m>c_n=\sum_{i+j=n}a_ib_j</m> for <m>n \ge 2</m>, then
          <me>
            |c_n|
            =
            \left|\sum_{i+j=n}\frac{(-1)^{i+j}}{\sqrt{ij}}\right|
            =
            \sum_{i+j=n}\frac{1}{\sqrt{ij}}.
          </me>
          For <m>i,j \ge 1</m> with <m>i+j=n</m>, we have
          <m>ij \lt (i+j)^2=n^2</m>, so
          <me>
            \frac{1}{\sqrt{ij}} &gt; \frac{1}{n}.
          </me>
          Since there are <m>n-1</m> such pairs, it follows that
          <me>
            |c_n| &gt; \frac{n-1}{n} \to 1.
          </me>
          Thus <m>c_n \not\to 0</m>, and the Cauchy product diverges by
          <xref ref="prop-divergence-test-series"/>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-series-raabe-test">
    <title>Raabe's Test</title>

    <p>
      The ratio test is inconclusive when
      <m>|x_{n+1}|/|x_n| \to 1</m>. Raabe's test refines that situation by
      measuring how quickly the ratio approaches <m>1</m>.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-raabe-test-series">
      <title>Raabe's Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>(x_n)</m> be a sequence of nonzero real numbers.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              If there exists <m>a&gt;1</m> such that
              <me>
                \left|\frac{x_{n+1}}{x_n}\right|
                \le
                1-\frac{a}{n+1}
              </me>
              for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>, then <m>\sum x_n</m>
              converges absolutely.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If there exists <m>a\le 1</m> such that
              <me>
                \left|\frac{x_{n+1}}{x_n}\right|
                \ge
                1-\frac{a}{n+1}
              </me>
              for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>, then <m>\sum x_n</m> does
              not converge absolutely.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          We first prove part (1). By discarding finitely many terms, we may
          assume the displayed inequality holds for every <m>n \ge 1</m>.
          Then
          <me>
            (n+1)|x_{n+1}|
            \le
            (n+1)|x_n|-a|x_n|
          </me>
          for every <m>n \ge 1</m>. Rearranging gives
          <me>
            0 \lt (a-1)|x_n|
            \le
            n|x_n|-(n+1)|x_{n+1}|.
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          Summing from <m>n=1</m> to <m>n=N</m>, we obtain
          <me>
            0
            \lt
            (a-1)\sum_{n=1}^N |x_n|
            \le
            |x_1|-(N+1)|x_{N+1}|
            \le
            |x_1|.
          </me>
          Hence the partial sums of <m>\sum |x_n|</m> are bounded above. By
          <xref ref="prop-nonnegative-series-criterion"/>, the series
          <m>\sum |x_n|</m> converges. Therefore <m>\sum x_n</m> converges
          absolutely.
        </p>

        <p>
          Now consider part (2). Again we may discard finitely many terms and
          assume the inequality holds for all <m>n \ge 1</m>. Then
          <me>
            (n+1)|x_{n+1}|
            \ge
            (n+1)|x_n|-a|x_n|
            \ge
            n|x_n|
          </me>
          for every <m>n \ge 1</m>. Thus the sequence <m>(n|x_n|)</m> is
          increasing. Since <m>x_n \ne 0</m>, we have <m>|x_1|&gt;0</m>, and
          therefore
          <me>
            |x_n| \ge \frac{|x_1|}{n}
          </me>
          for every <m>n \ge 1</m>. Because the harmonic series diverges by
          <xref ref="eg-harmonic-series-diverges"/>, the comparison test shows
          that <m>\sum |x_n|</m> diverges. So <m>\sum x_n</m> is not
          absolutely convergent.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-raabe-limit-form-series">
      <title>Limit Form of Raabe's Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>(x_n)</m> be a sequence of nonzero real numbers, and suppose
          the limit
          <me>
            a:=\lim (n+1)\left(1-\left|\frac{x_{n+1}}{x_n}\right|\right)
          </me>
          exists.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p>If <m>a&gt;1</m>, then <m>\sum x_n</m> converges absolutely.</p></li>
          <li><p>If <m>a&lt;1</m>, then <m>\sum x_n</m> does not converge absolutely.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>a&gt;1</m>. Choose a number <m>a_1</m> with
          <m>1 \lt a_1 \lt a</m>. Then for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>,
          <me>
            (n+1)\left(1-\left|\frac{x_{n+1}}{x_n}\right|\right) \gt a_1.
          </me>
          Rearranging, we obtain
          <me>
            \left|\frac{x_{n+1}}{x_n}\right|
            \lt
            1-\frac{a_1}{n+1}
          </me>
          eventually. Part (1) of <xref ref="prop-raabe-test-series"/> now
          shows that <m>\sum x_n</m> converges absolutely.
        </p>

        <p>
          Suppose instead that <m>a&lt;1</m>. Choose <m>a_1</m> with
          <m>a \lt a_1 \lt 1</m>. Then for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>,
          <me>
            (n+1)\left(1-\left|\frac{x_{n+1}}{x_n}\right|\right) \lt a_1,
          </me>
          so
          <me>
            \left|\frac{x_{n+1}}{x_n}\right|
            \gt
            1-\frac{a_1}{n+1}
          </me>
          eventually. Part (2) of
          <xref ref="prop-raabe-test-series"/> implies that <m>\sum x_n</m>
          is not absolutely convergent.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>

    <example xml:id="eg-raabe-p-series">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Raabe's test recovers the <m>p</m>-series criterion for
          <m>p \ne 1</m>. Let <m>x_n=1/n^p</m>. Then
          <me>
            \left|\frac{x_{n+1}}{x_n}\right|
            =
            \left(\frac{n}{n+1}\right)^p.
          </me>
          A short computation shows
          <me>
            \lim (n+1)\left(1-\left(\frac{n}{n+1}\right)^p\right)=p.
          </me>
          Therefore <xref ref="cor-raabe-limit-form-series"/> gives absolute
          convergence when <m>p&gt;1</m> and failure of absolute convergence
          when <m>p&lt;1</m>. Since the terms are nonnegative, this means the
          series diverges when <m>p&lt;1</m>. The case <m>p=1</m> is
          inconclusive for Raabe's test.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <conclusion>
    <p>
      References: compare <xref ref="biblio-rudin-pma"/>, Chapter 3, for
      Cauchy products, and <xref ref="biblio-bartle-sherbert"/> for Raabe's
      test and related refinements of the ratio test.
    </p>
  </conclusion>
</section>
